### Ethnobotany of Bryophytes
- Ethnobryology
	- Term from 50 years ago
- Partially responsible for oxygenation
- Colonized land, 430MYA
	- Evolved from green algae
- Nonvascular
	- Possibly why they're so thin?
- Moss leaf is one cell thick
	- No protective cuticle
- Root-analogues called rhizoids
	- ![Rhizoids-on-liverworts.png](data:image/png;base64,)
- Tiny spiral leaves
	- No complex structures like roots of veins to move water/food
- Rhizoids directly absorb resources from soil
- Leaves are 1-cell-thin, chlorophyll photosynthetic structures
- Sphagnum genus
	- Moss accumulates very gradually
	- Grows in [[Unsorted/California\|california]] around bogs
- Has been used for:
	- bandages
	- bedding
	- sponges
		- 22x its weight in water
	- medicine (antibiotic)
	- dyes
	- paintbrushes
	- firestarting
	- roofing
- Crossbreeds between species:
	- Has hybrid vigor
		- Positive traits of each parent species
	- Sterile
		- When hybrids CAN produce seeds, those seeds will yield "something else"
	- Hybrids in commercial farming can't have their seeds saved
		- GMO Companies love it
